abstract: Down-town merchants are very indignant over the action of the trunk railroads as detailed in yesterday's TIMES. They say that it is a mistaken notion to suppose that they derive any advantage from a railroad war. abstract: At Trinity Church the festival of the resurrection was observed with all the wealth of music, profusion of decorations, and grandeur of ritual for which that time-honored shrine of Episcopatianism has become famous. The services were not, it should be remembered, characterized by that gaudy display and wearisome ceremonial peculiar to the extreme ritualistic churches of this City, but were carried cut with all the imposing ceremonies of cathedral worship, no celebrated in England.

abstract: At the Anthon Memorial Church, West Forty-eighth-street, the entire chancel was richly adorned with floral designs appropriate to the season. Over the screen above the altar were the words "Christ is risen," in white flowers, on a background of ivy and smilax. Directly beneath the motto was a cross of lilies and tuberosos, and at each extremity of the screen were groups of calla lilies and tropical plants.

Chamberlain, he remained over for the purpose of preparing an address to the country in reply. He mapped out the document, which was to be a complete denial of all the allegations made by his competitor, and had commenced its preparation, when a number of his friends called upon him and strongly advised against it.

abstract: A young man calling himself Seth Hopkinson snatched Miss Clara Goodman's pocket-book from her hand in Fulton-street yesterday after noon. abstract: Judge John E. King, appointed Collector of the port of New-Orleans, is represented to have been a Union man throughout the late war. Wells at the close of the late war, but he declined the office.
